;; **
;;; As the above result shows, this is indeed possible.
;;; 
;;; > Note: There are indeed _two_ possible matches, since the roles of the nodes (as source or target of the `rel` edge) can be reversed. (More about this in section "_Alternative matches and equivalence_" below.) 
;;; 
;;; .
;;; > Note: this is the point in the tutorial when we start talking about "**_grapes_**" (**grap**h **e**numeration**s**) rather than graphs when referring to the input or output of operations.
;;; 
;;; .
;;; 
;;; ##### Identification condition
;;; 
;;; The identification condition (IDC) requires that graph elements to be deleted must be uniquely identified by elements in the rule's left-hand side. As an example, consider the following rule `delhello`, which matches two `Hello` nodes and deletes one of them.
;; **

;; @@
(rule delhello []
   (read 
      (node h:Hello)
      (node h2:Hello))
   (delete h))
