;; **
;;; > **Caution**: Since graph isomorphism checking is expensive, the current implementation _GrapeVine's_ identity checker is based on _bisimulation_. Graphs that are not bisimular are guaranteed to be structurally distinct. However, bimilar graphs are not necessarily structurally identical. Therefore, there is a chance that filtered rule application may remove graphs that are _not_ true duplicates. A future version of _GrapeVine_ may do confirmatory isomorphism tests, similar to what has been implemented in [GROOVE](https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&rct=j&q=&esrc=s&source=web&cd=&ved=2ahUKEwjOxt3A_cv3AhVrGDQIHbvRDYIQFnoECCAQAQ&url=https%3A%2F%2Fjournal.ub.tu-berlin.de%2Feceasst%2Farticle%2Fdownload%2F77%2F84&usg=AOvVaw3QwJkVQFzJbEG_THffmCqm). 
;;; >
;;; > For now, though, _GrapeVine_ users must keep in mind that the current duplicate filter in _GrapeVine_ is just another approximation of the formal semantics of graph transformations. More precisly, it is a _lower_ approximation, while unfiltered rule application is an _upper_ approximation.
;; **

;; **
;;; ### Applying rules to _grapes_ (containing multiple graphs)
;;; 
;;; So far, we only applied rules to single graphs, i.e., _grapes_ with a single element. However, rules can also be applied to _grapes_ that enumerate multiple graphs. Consider the _grape_ produced by the following statement. (We create a graph with two `Hello` nodes and then apply rule `world` with an unfiltered rule application.) The _grape_ should have two graphs: 
;; **

;; @@
(-> (newgrape) hello hello world view)
